:::summary
The Byzantine Empire (330–1453 AD) was the eastern continuation of the Roman Empire, centered at Constantinople — the city founded by Emperor Constantine on the site of ancient Byzantium. For more than a thousand years, Byzantium preserved the heritage of Rome and Greece, produced magnificent Christian art and architecture, maintained Orthodox Christianity, and stood as the principal bulwark of Christian civilization against Persian, Arab, and finally Ottoman expansion. Its fall to the Ottoman Turks in 1453 marks the conventional end of the Middle Ages.
:::

